ce:section.ce:para:
The as-prepared MCQDs are characterized morphologically by TEM and AFM. The TEM image shows that the MCQDs were well distributed, ranging from 2 to 10 nm (Fig. 1
                        a, Inset). The AFM image confirms that the MCQDs are dispersed homogeneously, and few carbon dots aggregated with the height of 7.59 nm (Fig. 1b), the corresponding particle size graph shows that the carbon dots were in the size of 2–10 nm (Fig. 1d). The 3D height profile also visualizes the even distribution of MCQDs (Fig. 1c). The schematic representation of MCQDs synthesis and the applications is presented in (Scheme 1
                        ).

MCQDs were characterized analytically to study the surface functional properties (Fig. 2
                        ). The FTIR analysis shows distinct peaks at 3361 cm−1, 1640 cm−1, 1539 cm−1, 1050 cm−1, 652 cm−1 which attributes the –OH, CO, CC, C–H functional groups, respectively. The FTIR study suggests that the MCQDs have hydroxy groups on their surface and has negatively charged moieties, which accounts for their water solubility [Dager et al., 2019]. In order to study in detail, the surface functional groups of Cesium were analyzed, which shown minor peaks in the range of 3500-3000 cm−1, indicating the presence of the C–H group. MCQDs with Cesium ions have also been analyzed, which shows shifting in OH groups at the 3000 cm−1 range, confirming that the quantum dots were reacted with Cesium and thus resulted in sensing [Mo et al., 2020]. XPS analysis was performed in order to study and analyze the complete chemical and elemental composition of MCQDs and also composition of MCQDs after sensing cesium. The XPS analysis of MCQDs shows the three major peaks of C1s at 285 eV, N1s at 400 eV, O1s at 532 eV binding energies (Fig. 3
                        a Black trace). Furthermore, the high resolution deconvoluted spectra of C1s shows peaks at 284.8 eV, 286.2 eV, 288.06 eV of C–C, C–O–C, O–CO functional groups respectively (Fig. 3b). In case of N1s deconvoluted spectrum the functional groups such as CN–C, C–NH2, C-(NH)-C (Fig. 3c) were analyzed at the binding energies of 397.2 eV, 399.7 eV, 401.7 eV respectively. The functional groups of CO, C–O, NO were observed at 531 eV, 532 eV, 533.2 eV binding energies (Fig. 3d) respectively. The FTIR and XPS analysis shows that MCQDs has functional groups facilitating its aqueous nature, which is beneficial for the sensing application [Ayiania et al., 2020]. On the other hand, the MCQDs with cesium were also analyzed by XPS which shows the major peaks of C1s, N1s, O1s and Cs3d groups and the deconvoluted spectrum of C1s shows similar peaks as MCQDs with reduced intensity and an additional peak at 284 eV of C–C denoting the defective carbon formed after the reaction between cesium, in case of N1s similar deconvoluted peaks were observed with reduction in intensity at C–NH2 representing the plausible reaction between the amine functional group and the cesium. And in case of O1s, few peaks in the range of 527–537 eV representing the formation of metal oxides which further confirms the sensing of cesium, thus forming the metal oxides. Few minor peaks were observed in the range of 720–740 eV binding energies denoting the cesium Cs3d functional groups after sensing of cesium (Fig S2a-d) [Cho et al., 2012]. According to the analytical data, we derived a plausible mechanism for sensing of cesium by using MCQDs, which is presented in Fig. S3. From the XPS and FTIR analysis, MCQDs exhibits functional groups such as hydroxyl, amine groups on their surface facilitating the electron transfer process from surface groups to cesium ion, there by leads to the quenching in fluorescence (Yang et al., 2014).
